2026-05-21 | Check if All Bits are Set

	Question
Return true if every bit is set.
	Key Insight
A number with all bits set looks like:
		1
		11
		111
		1111
		...
Such numbers satisfy:
		n & (n + 1) == 0
Why?
Example:
		n = 7  → 111
		n+1=8 →1000
		111 & 1000 = 0
	Approach
1.	Check:
		(n & (n + 1)) == 0
2.	If true:
		all bits are set
3.	Otherwise:
		not all bits are set
	Time Complexity
	O(1)
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    bool isBitSet(int n) {
        return (n & (n + 1)) == 0;
    }
};
	Key Insight
Numbers containing all 1s in binary
have a very special property:
		adding 1 creates power of 2  
That makes:
		n & (n+1) = 0.
